Communication
department rearranges
class registration

KATE LAUGHLIN
The Pitt News

Ask any student who registers with the communication

. department and most will undoubtedly remember the morning

of last March 15.

By 6 a.m. the line to register for fall classes was already
snaking its way around the outskirts of Thackeray Hall where
registration wouldn’t officially begin until, 8 a.m. The line,
ﬁlled with communication majors clutching their ideal class
schedules,-had begun to form as early as 3:30 a.m.

With increasing numbers of communication majors at the
University and not enough classes to satisfy them, competition
was tight for seats in many of the sought after upper-level class-
es.

Some students felt the only way to win in this ﬁrst come,
first served system was to drag themselves out of bed before
dawn and wait in line. hours before registration even began.
Because of this, the department is now instituting a new proce-
dure for registering its students, effective this semester.

“We are ‘switching from a stand—in—line registration to an
in—house registration,” communication adviser John Gareis
said.

That means that after their usual group advising sessions
next Tuesday and Wednesday, students will not have to take
their prospective schedules — basically no more than wish lists
— to Thackeray themselves on Thursday morning, when regis-
tration officially opens. Instead the paperwork from students in
each group session will be collected and at 7:45 Thursday
morning, newly hired personnel will register each group elec-
tronically in the chronological order of the group sessions. This
gives graduating seniors the highest priority. The next group
sessions will follow the same procedure.

“We think tl1at’s the fairest way to do it,” Gareis said.

One of the many problems last year, Gareis said, was that
with students in other College of Arts and Sciences depart-
ments registering at the same time, some popular communica-
tion classes ﬁlled up after 10 minutes.

“Now communications students will -have an edge,” he
added.

Melis Ersoy, a communication major graduating this
spring, put her time in last semester. “It was hard because I was
afraid I wouldn’t get the classes I needed even though I was
registering as a senior,” she said. A _

The registration procedure isn’t the only aspect of the
department undergoing improvements, either. There has been
anincrease in personnel, both advising and teaching staff, and
also an increase in the availability of certain classes.

According to Gareis, after registration began last spring,
the communication department added six or seven more thou-
sand-level classes to its fall schedule to accommodate the stu-
dent demand.

