Nordenberg honored by
Jewish National Fund

GREG HELLER-LABELLE I
Staff Writer

The Jewish National Fund honored
Chancellor Mark Nordenberg with its
highest honor, the Tree of Life award,
at a celebration dinner on Monday
night.

The evening’s events Ibcused on
Nordenberg’s accomplishments in the
ﬁeld of education, beginning with his
award-winning teaching at Pitt’s Law
School and culminating with his inau-
guration as Pitt chancellor in 1995.

Along with plenty of Pitt football
jokes, the presenters pointed out
Nordenberg’s many positions on local
boards and panels as well as his roles in
various civic activities.

Steven H. Schwartz, JNF’s Western
Pennsylvania regional president, intro-
duced Nordenberg, calling him “the
highest example of spirit, community

_ and dedication.”

Former award winners were pre-
sent at the celebration, along with
Pittsburgh notables including Howard
Hanna and Mayor Tom Murphy and
numerous area figures in higher educa-
tion.

Nordenberg’s close friend and for-
mer award winner Dan‘ Rooney, presi-
dent of the Pittsburgh Steelers, present-
ed the award to Nordenberg. _

After begging for “a little patience”
for both the Panthers and Steelers foot-
ball clubs, Rooney recalled
Nordenberg’s election to chancellor
after an interim term in 1995.

“The University had to bring conﬁ-

dence and integrity back to Pittsburgh,”

Rooney said.

Rooney ‘pointed to signs of Pitt’s
success under Nordenberg, including
the construction of the Petersen Events

. Center and the fact that Pitt produced

Marshall Scholars in both 2000 and
2001. '

“The University of Pittsburgh is '

one of the finest and most productive in

the world,” Rooney said.

Nordenberg said that he was “hon—
ored to be associated with the other
leaders in the region who have come
together,” and recalled memories of his
ﬁrst trip to Israel.

“I can still feel the excitement of
being in Israel for the first time,” he
said. “I had never experienced quite the
same feeling before  feelings ground-
ed in the sense that that everyone
around me cared deeply.”

Nordenberg related that sense of
caring to the kindness shown in this
country since Sept. 11.

He spoke about his second landing
in Israel, when his plane out of Tel Aviv
lost an engine’ after about 45 minutes
and had to turn around. Nordenberg
recalled seeing the “large collection of
fire trucks and ambulances”. on the tar-
mac. - ,
“When my feet touched the soil of
Israel, I felt safe and secure,”
Nordenberg said. “I think that would be
our collective wish tonight: safety and
security for Israel.” .

The award, presented “in recogni-
tion of outstanding professional and
humanitarian leadership, dedication to
Israeli-American friendship and devo-
tion to world peace,” also called for a

‘forest to be planted in Israel in

Nordenberg’s name. Trees are a very
important symbol of the JNF, which has
planted more than 210 million trees in
Israel in- the country’s 50-year history.

Nordenberg mentioned the
progress that the JNF had made in revi-
talizing Israel.

“We saw green land in areas that
had been deserts,” Nordenberg said. “It
was indeed the holy land.”

Nordenberg said that he was ‘‘hon—

‘ ored and humbled” by the award and

the forest, which will be in American
Independence Park in Jerusalem.
“Being a part of this process is one

of the most meaningful things that has _

happened in my life,” he said.

