EDITORIAL

In land of free speech, why force
  the Pledge of Allegiance?

Patriotism isn’t always predictable.
Some people feel national pride watch-
ing ﬁreworks displays on Independence
Day; others might get the same feeling
listening to Bruce Springsteen, watch-
ing a baseball game or driving cross-
country on Route 66.

In short, people experience patrio-
tism in different ways, at different times
and in different places. You can’t always
predict this feeling, and you certainly
carmot legislate it. .

Yet the ridiculous notion of mandat-
ing patriotism seems to be the objective
of legislators in the state House of
Representatives, who passed a bill on
Tuesday requiring students in
Pennsylvania to recite the Pledge of
Allegiance or sing the national anthem
each morning.

Passed by a vote of 200 to one, the
same bill also requires all classrooms to
display the American ﬂag. Students may
be exempted from the pledge or from
singing the national anthem only if they
have their parents’ written permission.

The inefﬁcacy and utter pointless-
ness of such a bill is striking.

. How would these provisions be
enforced? Certainly our law ' enforce-
ment agencies havegreater socialills to
focus on than the failure of schoolchild-

ren to recite the pledge.

Furthermore, pride and commit-
ment to one’s country — the values
espoused in the Pledge- of Allegiance
and “The Star-Spangled Barmer” — are
meaningful only if they are genuinely
felt. A seventh grader mumbling the
words to the pledge at 7:30 a.m.,‘ when
he is still half-asleep, is not necessarily
experiencing true patriotism.

Our lawmakers carmot force anyone
to feel patriotic, no matter how many
statutes they approve. What they can do
is focus on issues that matter, working
to lower crime rates, improve thezstate
system of education and otherwise
strive to better the commonwealth. By
doing so they will increase the genuine
pride we feel for our state and our coun-

Finally, children — and adolescents
in particular — may find that they have
religious or moral values that differ
from those-expressed in the pledge and
the national anthem, and perhaps that
diverge from those of their parents.

This new bill — if approved by. the
state Senate — leaves those students

‘without a means of expressing them-

selves; In our land of choice and oppor-
tunity, there is something disturbingly
un—American about forced conformity.

